dist/research/chebyshev-option-surfaces/summary/index.html:171:<section id="bottom-line"><h2 id="7-bottom-line">7. Bottom line</h2><aside class="summary-box summary-box-take"> <p class="summary-box-title">Bottom line</p> <div class="summary-box-body"> <p>The core achievement is structural: choose coordinates and warps that match market geometry, choose a tensor basis whose derivatives close, convert every static restriction into sparse operators, and solve one convex projection problem in coefficient space. With that backbone in place, Hamiltonian fog is exactly the right add-on: local, noise-aware, and subordinate to the global arbitrage-free surface.</p> </div> </aside></section> </article> <article class="card" data-reveal> <p class="meta-label mb-2">Linked visual guide</p> <h2 class="mb-3 text-3xl">Arbitrage-Free Option Price Surfaces via Chebyshev Tensor Bases and a Hamiltonian Fog Post-Fit</h2> <p class="body-copy mb-5">Fit the arbitrage-carrying forward-discounted call surface directly in price space, enforce static no-arbitrage through sparse linear operators, and use a local Hamiltonian fog only as a patch-wise post-fit where quotes are inconsistent.</p> <a href="/research/chebyshev-option-surfaces" class="subtle-link text-sm">
